<DOC><DOCNO> AP890316-0179 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 2032EST</FILEID><FIRST>u w AM-ArmsFraud 1stld-writethru a0791 03-16 0398</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Arms Fraud, 1st ld-writethru, a0791,380</SECOND><HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT that Reese pleaded guilty to conspiracyand filing a false statement, not to conspiracy and bribery</HEAD><BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A U.S. Army colonel who supervised militarysales to El Salvador was indicted Thursday on charges he solicitedand took more than $70,000 in bribes from the president of anIllinois gun maker.   Col. Juan Lopez de la Cruz, a U.S. military advisor in SanSalvador between 1982 and 1984, was named in a seven-countindictment that charged conspiracy, bribery and making falsestatements, and aiding and abetting the filing of false claims.   The indictment, returned by a federal grand jury in Alexandria,Va., accused Lopez of conspiring with Dennis J. Reese, president ofSpringfield Armory, Inc. to take bribes and to circumvent rules ofthe foreign military sales program.   The indictment charged that Lopez solicited and received $70,000in bribes from Reese, who pleaded guilty last month to conspiracyand to filing a false statement. Reese also purchased, at Lopez'srequest, a $4,722 Rolex watch for the colonel.   In return for the bribes, Lopez is accused of signing falsedocuments that enabled Springfield Armory to be reimbursed for salesof weapons to the Salvadoran government, including $94,600 in phonysales commissions.   The indictment charged that Lopez and Reese arranged for falsecommissions to be paid to two Salvadorans they designated as agentsto circumvent regulations governing the military sales.   Lopez directed Reese to make out checks to the Salvadorans, whocashed them and returned the money to Reese _ minus their fee, theindictment said.   Lopez, who was the advisor to the Salvadoran Military Group,which advised the Salvadoran government on weapons sales, wasaccused of signing false government documents stating thatcommissions had been paid on the sale of $3.7 million worth offirearms.   He is also accused of aiding and abetting Reese's filing of falseclaims for reimbursement of $94,600 from the Defense Department forthe false commissions.   If found guilty of all seven counts, Lopez could be sentenced upto 15 years for each of the two bribery charges and five years foreach of the five remaining counts.   The bribery charges together would carry a fine of $210,000 whilethe other charges carry fines of $250,000 apiece.   Attempts to reach Lopez for comment were unsuccessful.</TEXT></DOC>